    <fr:title text="Separable space">Separable space</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A topological space is called separable if it contains a countable, dense subset. For a metric space, this means there exists a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> subset whose closure is the entire space.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>In the context of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link>, a Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is separable if and only if it has a countable <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link>. This is equivalent to saying that there exists a countable set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> such that the span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> is dense in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>For <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach spaces</fr:link>, separability means there exists a countable subset whose linear span is dense in the space.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Important examples of separable spaces include:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>The Euclidean spaces <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}^n]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p[a,b]]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \leq  p < \infty ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C[a,b]]]></fr:tex> of continuous functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a,b]]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The sequence spaces <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^p]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \leq  p < \infty ]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>Important non-separable spaces include:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>The space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> of essentially bounded measurable functions</fr:li>
<fr:li>The space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^\infty ]]></fr:tex> of bounded sequences</fr:li>
<fr:li>The space of all bounded linear operators on an infinite-dimensional Hilbert space</fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>Separability is a useful property in functional analysis as it often allows for the application of results that require countable operations, such as diagonal arguments and the ability to work with sequences rather than nets.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
