            <fr:title text="Countable">Countable</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countable if its elements can be arranged in a sequence (i.e., if there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and the set of natural numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, or a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countable if either:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is finite (i.e., there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{1, 2, ..., n\}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>), or</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countably infinite (i.e., there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>)</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Examples of countable sets include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The set of natural numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of integers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of rational numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of algebraic numbers</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>In contrast, the set of real numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is uncountable, as proven by Cantor's diagonal argument.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In functional analysis, the concept of countability is important in several contexts:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0026.xml" addr="FA-0026" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link> if and only if it has a countable <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0028.xml" addr="FA-0028" title="Schauder basis">Schauder basis</fr:link> in a Banach space is by definition countable</fr:li>
<fr:li>The spectrum of a compact operator on a Hilbert space is either finite or countably infinite with 0 as the only possible accumulation point</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1487</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0027</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0027.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A complete (in the sense of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:link>) <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link>) of H is also called an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Altenately</fr:strong>: An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0024.xml" addr="FA-0024" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> of H.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>N.B.</fr:strong>: This notion of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> is <fr:em>not quite the same</fr:em> as in the <fr:em>finite dimensional case</fr:em> (although it is a legitimate extension of it).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>There are other, quite different, notions of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> in <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0005.xml" addr="FA-0005" title="Infinite Dimensions">infinite dimensions</fr:link>. See for instance '<fr:link type="local" href="FA-0025.xml" addr="FA-0025" title="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:link>' which arises in some settings</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Theorem:</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0026.xml" addr="FA-0026" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> has a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> orthonormal <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1489</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0028</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0028.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Schauder basis">Schauder basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Schauder basis for a Banach space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a sequence of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty }]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that for every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex>, there exists a unique sequence of scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{a_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty }]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n=1}^{\infty } a_n e_n]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the series converges in the norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A Schauder basis differs from a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0025.xml" addr="FA-0025" title="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:link> in that it allows for infinite (but convergent) linear combinations of basis elements, making it more suitable for the study of infinite-dimensional Banach spaces.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every Schauder basis <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> comes with a sequence of coordinate functionals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n^*\}]]></fr:tex> in the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001Q.xml" addr="FA-001Q" title="Dual space">dual space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^*]]></fr:tex>, defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_n^*(x) = a_n]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_n]]></fr:tex> are the unique coefficients in the expansion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n} a_n e_n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Important properties of Schauder bases:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A Banach space with a Schauder basis is always <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0026.xml" addr="FA-0026" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>Not every separable Banach space has a Schauder basis (as proven by Per Enflo for certain spaces)</fr:li>
<fr:li>In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> is a Schauder basis</fr:li>
<fr:li>The standard examples of Schauder bases include the Haar system in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p[0,1]]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \leq  p < \infty ]]></fr:tex> and the trigonometric system in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2[0,2\pi ]]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
