            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countable if its elements can be arranged in a sequence (i.e., if there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and the set of natural numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, or a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countable if either:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is finite (i.e., there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{1, 2, ..., n\}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>), or</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is countably infinite (i.e., there exists a bijection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>)</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Examples of countable sets include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The set of natural numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of integers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of rational numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The set of algebraic numbers</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>In contrast, the set of real numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is uncountable, as proven by Cantor's diagonal argument.</fr:p>
