            <fr:anchor>1495</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
